    {
      "id": "2a51cd296876b9b5214106b82e8fedca40a6b260",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 7,
        "name": "Johann Lombardi",
        "email": "johann.lombardi@intel.com",
        "username": "johann",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-02-22 07:48:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5: Looks good to me, approved\n\nCould you please contact the original author of the patch and find out if he intends to push the patch for inclusion any time soon? If not, we should probably send it ourselves to fsdevel@ with performance number w/o Lustre (on ext4 directly).\n\ncc Jeff Mahoney who has been looking at our kernel patches lately.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "d0f5810d20772fc00f7746b3d9766b16b89c886a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 298,
        "name": "Jeff Mahoney",
        "email": "jeffm@suse.com",
        "username": "jeffm"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-22 22:28:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nSure, I'll take a deeper look for upstream inclusion. At a glance, I think it'll need significant updating.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "41cbb1776b88d6e3e129ab62e4854e89c6bed2a9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 298,
        "name": "Jeff Mahoney",
        "email": "jeffm@suse.com",
        "username": "jeffm"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-26 03:40:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nWhile I do believe that there is lock contention in the initialize case, I'd rather see performance numbers before actually implementing this change using i_lock.\n\nAs a first step, we can just replace the super-global dqptr_sem with a per-inode rw_semaphore and see how that works. Since it's trading a rw_semaphore for another, we don't need to deal with all of the other API changes until we see real benefit. Then we can look at the API changes. It may well be that the best way to do it, if we're already claiming a reference for each dquot struct before submission, to clone inode->i_dquot before dirtying and then we can avoid the silly locking in inode_mark_dquot_dirty.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "8a0929082a22af1d237c96e1f24f129f7ffe86fb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 101,
        "name": "Lai Siyao",
        "email": "lai.siyao@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "laisiyao"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-27 06:31:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nIt's not easy to replace the global dqptr_sem with a per-inode semaphore because in functions like remove_dquot_ref() inode_lock needs to be taken before access inode, however inode_lock is a spinlock.\n\nI'll update the patch, but still with i_lock.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "e15bb51da2c4c0c2eafd42e2d6ce975628271b46",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 298,
        "name": "Jeff Mahoney",
        "email": "jeffm@suse.com",
        "username": "jeffm"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-27 14:05:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nI'm not sure how you came to that analysis.\n\nReplacing the per-super rw_semaphore with a per-inode rw_semaphore is straightforward. Outside of the initialization, it's literally a search/replace operation.\n\nWe *don't* need to take i_lock before touching the inode generally. inode->i_lock only protects a few of the inode fields; This patch is extending inode->i_lock to protect another one of them.\n\nI've been talking this over with Jan Kara, who's in my team and the author of much of the quota code. The path forward is probably to drop the rw lock entirely and use SRCU instead.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "61ed39d7d652bf629c6df9703197dbc0b3598640",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 101,
        "name": "Lai Siyao",
        "email": "lai.siyao@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "laisiyao"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-27 16:33:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nCould you take a look at drop_dquot_ref()? The lock order is dqptr_sem -> inode_lock, if dqptr_sem is replaced with a per-inode semaphore, it will be taken inside inode_lock, that's not viable. What's your suggestion?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "7b1f523cf374a8a8020f0bf9369c380b69f18147",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 298,
        "name": "Jeff Mahoney",
        "email": "jeffm@suse.com",
        "username": "jeffm"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-27 16:52:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nOops, yep. You're absolutely right. I'd still prefer not to use the patch as-is. I don't expect it'll be accepted upstream.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "a8e7a45e79541613e5f4c226dc6f813157543475",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 7,
        "name": "Johann Lombardi",
        "email": "johann.lombardi@intel.com",
        "username": "johann",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-02-27 17:44:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nThe performance improvement is significant. Lai can probably provide numbers.\n\nA per-inode rw semaphore might not be enough, i am afraid, although it doesn't hurt to test. If reusing the i_lock isn't acceptable, we can still introduce yet another per-inode spinlock or using SRCU as suggested by Jeff.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "28fe7aa433a13058ca2ab642fc236440bfe9eb1e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 298,
        "name": "Jeff Mahoney",
        "email": "jeffm@suse.com",
        "username": "jeffm"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-28 14:07:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nAnother possibility is to look at what add_dquot_ref does WRT to the spinlock. drop_dquot_ref have similar rules. Once the quota is suspended, new inodes won't have dquot structures associated with them so it should be similarly safe.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "c8f85a6cec83ebe307029bfe1d2c905f2834ec14",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 101,
